WEBVTT

1
00:02:46.293 --> 00:02:47.294
No!

2
00:04:09.584 --> 00:04:11.552
- ls everything ready?
- Oui, monsieur.


3
00:04:11.628 --> 00:04:13.926
You have your instructions?

4
00:04:30.605 --> 00:04:33.028
ls everything all right, Mrs. Ho?

5
00:04:34.401 --> 00:04:36.745
Dinner will be ready at 7:30.

6
00:04:50.041 --> 00:04:51.293
Good evening.

7
00:04:51.376 --> 00:04:53.174
Good evening. I don't know if...

8
00:04:53.253 --> 00:04:55.506
Yes indeed, sir,
you are expected, Colonel.


9
00:04:55.588 --> 00:04:58.182
May I take your coat?
It is Colonel Mustard, isn't it?


10
00:04:58.258 --> 00:05:01.102
- No, that's not my name. My name's...
- Forgive me, sir.


11
00:05:01.177 --> 00:05:04.306
Tonight, you may well feel obliged
to my employer


12
00:05:04.389 --> 00:05:06.642
for the use of an alias.

13
00:05:18.278 --> 00:05:20.326
And who are you, sir?

14
00:05:20.405 --> 00:05:22.203
I'm Wadsworth, sir.

15
00:05:22.282 --> 00:05:23.784
The butler.

16
00:05:31.875 --> 00:05:35.300
Yvette, could you attend to the colonel
and give him anything he requires.


17
00:05:35.378 --> 00:05:37.301
Within reason, that is.

18
00:05:38.548 --> 00:05:40.471
Wadsworth, I was...

19
00:05:46.556 --> 00:05:48.934
Do come in, madam. 
You are expected.

20
00:05:49.017 --> 00:05:50.485
Do you know who I am?

21
00:05:50.560 --> 00:05:54.064
Only that you are to be known
as Mrs. White.


22
00:05:54.147 --> 00:05:56.741
Yes. It said so
in the letter. But why?

23
00:06:14.084 --> 00:06:16.007
May I introduce you?

24
00:06:16.086 --> 00:06:18.839
Mrs. White, this is Yvette, the maid.

25
00:06:18.922 --> 00:06:21.300
I see you know each other.

26
00:06:23.134 --> 00:06:24.636
- Hello.
- Hello.


27
00:07:00.046 --> 00:07:01.923
Want a lift?

28
00:07:02.006 --> 00:07:03.553
Yes, please.

29
00:07:06.761 --> 00:07:09.230
Thanks. I'm late for a dinner date.

30
00:07:09.305 --> 00:07:11.603
Me, too. Where are you going?

31
00:07:12.350 --> 00:07:14.102
Let's see.

32
00:07:14.477 --> 00:07:16.605
Hill House, off Route 41.

33
00:07:16.688 --> 00:07:18.782
Wait a minute. 
Let me look at that.

34
00:07:18.857 --> 00:07:22.031
That's where I'm going.
I got a letter like this.


35
00:07:32.787 --> 00:07:35.290
And this is Mrs. Peacock.

36
00:07:35.790 --> 00:07:37.133
- How do you do.
- Hello.


37
00:07:37.292 --> 00:07:39.590
Yvette, will you go and check
that dinner will be ready


38
00:07:39.669 --> 00:07:42.764
as soon as all the guests have arrived.

39
00:07:58.688 --> 00:08:01.066
Is this the right address
to meet Mr. Boddy?


40
00:08:01.149 --> 00:08:02.321
You must be Mr. Green.

41
00:08:02.400 --> 00:08:04.698
- Yes.
- Sit!


42
00:08:04.777 --> 00:08:06.779
No. Not you, sir.

43
00:08:13.036 --> 00:08:15.835
It should be just off there.

44
00:08:23.504 --> 00:08:24.847
That must be it.

45
00:08:27.842 --> 00:08:30.265
Why has the car stopped?

46
00:08:30.345 --> 00:08:31.597
It's frightened.

47
00:09:07.715 --> 00:09:08.716
Aah!

48
00:09:21.020 --> 00:09:23.193
What a godforsaken place.

49
00:09:26.609 --> 00:09:30.489
Professor Plum and Miss Scarlet.
I didn't realize you were acquainted.


50
00:09:30.571 --> 00:09:32.118
We weren't.

51
00:09:38.246 --> 00:09:41.295
May I present
Professor Plum and Miss Scarlet.


52
00:09:54.095 --> 00:09:56.644
Of course, since you've each been
addressed by a pseudonym,


53
00:09:56.723 --> 00:10:00.318
you'll have realized that nobody here
is being addressed by their real name.


54
00:10:05.940 --> 00:10:07.487
Dinner.

55
00:10:08.151 --> 00:10:09.653
I'm sorry.

56
00:10:09.986 --> 00:10:12.455
I'm a little accident-prone.

57
00:10:22.749 --> 00:10:25.047
You'll find your names
beside your places.


58
00:10:25.126 --> 00:10:26.753
Please be seated.

59
00:10:35.470 --> 00:10:37.347
Is this place for you?

60
00:10:37.430 --> 00:10:39.353
Indeed, no, sir.
I'm merely a humble butler.


61
00:10:39.432 --> 00:10:40.854
What exactly do you do?

62
00:10:40.933 --> 00:10:42.856
- I buttle, sir.
- Which means what?


63
00:10:42.935 --> 00:10:44.733
The butler is head of the kitchen
and dining room.


64
00:10:44.812 --> 00:10:46.906
I keep everything tidy. That's all.

65
00:10:46.981 --> 00:10:50.110
Well, what's all this about, butler,
this dinner party?


66
00:10:50.193 --> 00:10:53.447
"Ours not to reason why,
ours but to do and die."


67
00:10:53.529 --> 00:10:54.621
Die?

68
00:10:54.739 --> 00:10:56.912
Merely quoting, sir,
from Alfred, Lord Tennyson.


69
00:10:57.408 --> 00:10:59.376
I prefer Kipling myself.

70
00:10:59.452 --> 00:11:02.956
"The female of the species
is more deadly than the male."


71
00:11:03.039 --> 00:11:04.507
You like Kipling, Miss Scarlet?

72
00:11:04.582 --> 00:11:05.799
Sure. I'll eat anything.

73
00:11:07.335 --> 00:11:09.258
Shark's fin soup, madam.

74
00:11:09.337 --> 00:11:10.429
So, is this for our host?

75
00:11:10.505 --> 00:11:12.599
No, sir.
For the seventh guest, Mr. Boddy.


76
00:11:12.673 --> 00:11:14.721
I thought Mr. Boddy was our host.

77
00:11:14.801 --> 00:11:16.223
So did I.

78
00:11:16.302 --> 00:11:19.272
So, who is our host, Mr. Wadsworth?

79
00:11:22.600 --> 00:11:23.852
Well, I'm gonna start while it's still hot.

80
00:11:23.935 --> 00:11:26.063
Now, shouldn't we wait
for the other guest?


81
00:11:26.145 --> 00:11:28.239
I'll keep something warm for him.

82
00:11:28.314 --> 00:11:30.533
What'd you have in mind, dear?

83
00:12:01.764 --> 00:12:05.439
Well, someone's got to break the ice
and it might as well be me.


84
00:12:05.518 --> 00:12:08.647
I mean, I'm used to being a hostess.
It's part of my husband's work.


85
00:12:08.729 --> 00:12:11.278
And It's always difficult
when a group of new friends


86
00:12:11.357 --> 00:12:13.780
meet together for the first time
to get acquainted.


87
00:12:13.860 --> 00:12:16.784
So, I'm perfectly prepared to
start the ball rolling.


88
00:12:16.863 --> 00:12:19.958
I mean, I have absolutely no idea
what we're doing here


89
00:12:20.032 --> 00:12:22.455
or what I'm doing here
or what this place is about,


90
00:12:22.535 --> 00:12:25.459
but I am determined to enjoy myself.

91
00:12:25.538 --> 00:12:26.960
I'm very intrigued.

92
00:12:27.039 --> 00:12:29.383
And, my, this soup's delicious, isn't it?

93
00:12:31.919 --> 00:12:35.298
You say you are used to being a
hostess as part of your husband's work?


94
00:12:35.381 --> 00:12:39.727
Yes, it's an integral part of your life
when you're the wife of a...


95
00:12:40.553 --> 00:12:43.477
But then I forgot, we're not supposed to
say who we really are,


96
00:12:43.556 --> 00:12:45.558
though heavens to Betsy
I don't know why.


97
00:12:45.725 --> 00:12:47.523
Don't you?

98
00:12:47.643 --> 00:12:49.645
I know who you are.

99
00:12:49.770 --> 00:12:50.817
Aren't you gonna tell us?

100
00:12:50.897 --> 00:12:52.114
How do you know who I am?

101
00:12:52.190 --> 00:12:54.192
I work in Washington, too.

102
00:12:54.275 --> 00:12:55.948
Washington?
So, you're a politician's wife?


103
00:12:56.027 --> 00:12:57.654
Yes, I am.

104
00:12:57.862 --> 00:12:59.739
Well, come on then.
Who's your husband?


105
00:13:06.412 --> 00:13:09.586
- So, what does your husband do?
- Nothing.


106
00:13:09.707 --> 00:13:11.084
Nothing?

107
00:13:11.250 --> 00:13:14.880
Well, he just lies around
on his back all day.


108
00:13:14.962 --> 00:13:16.339
Sounds like hard work to me.

109
00:13:21.052 --> 00:13:22.474
I'm sorry.

110
00:13:24.514 --> 00:13:26.357
I'm afraid I'm a little bit accident-prone.

111
00:13:26.432 --> 00:13:27.900
Watch it.

112
00:13:31.437 --> 00:13:32.780
Excusez-moi.

113
00:13:45.368 --> 00:13:47.496
My, oh.

114
00:13:47.745 --> 00:13:51.875
Mmm. This is one of my favorite recipes.

115
00:13:51.999 --> 00:13:53.501
I know, madam.

116
00:13:56.170 --> 00:13:59.891
So, what do you do in Washington D.C.,
Mr. Green?


117
00:13:59.966 --> 00:14:02.890
Come on. What do you do?

118
00:14:02.969 --> 00:14:06.064
I mean, how are we to get acquainted if
we don't say anything about ourselves?


119
00:14:06.138 --> 00:14:08.140
Perhaps he doesn't want to get
acquainted with you.


120
00:14:08.266 --> 00:14:09.609
Well, I'm sure I don't know.

121
00:14:09.684 --> 00:14:11.732
But if I wasn't trying to keep
the conversation going,


122
00:14:11.811 --> 00:14:14.655
then we would just be sitting here in
an embarrassed silence.


123
00:14:14.730 --> 00:14:17.153
Are you afraid of silence, Mrs. Peacock?

124
00:14:17.233 --> 00:14:18.780
Yes... No, why?

125
00:14:18.859 --> 00:14:20.736
Just seems to me that
you seem to suffer


126
00:14:20.820 --> 00:14:22.914
from what we call "pressure of speech."

127
00:14:22.989 --> 00:14:25.208
"We"? Who's "we"? 
Are you a shrink?

128
00:14:25.283 --> 00:14:27.877
I do know a little bit about
psychological medicine, yes.


129
00:14:27.994 --> 00:14:30.122
You're a doctor?

130
00:14:30.204 --> 00:14:31.797
I am, but I don't practice.

131
00:14:31.872 --> 00:14:33.294
Practice makes perfect.

132
00:14:33.374 --> 00:14:35.718
I think most men need a little practice,

133
00:14:35.793 --> 00:14:37.340
don't you, Mrs. Peacock?

134
00:14:37.420 --> 00:14:39.093
What do you do, Professor?

135
00:14:39.171 --> 00:14:41.048
I work for UNO,
the United Nations Organization.


136
00:14:41.132 --> 00:14:42.930
Another politician. Jesus!

137
00:14:43.009 --> 00:14:47.810
No, I work for a branch of UNO. WHO,
the World Health Organization.


138
00:14:47.888 --> 00:14:49.936
Well, what's your area
of special concern?


139
00:14:50.016 --> 00:14:51.893
Family planning.

140
00:14:51.976 --> 00:14:54.024
What about you, Colonel,
are you a real colonel?


141
00:14:54.103 --> 00:14:55.525
I am, sir.

142
00:14:55.605 --> 00:14:56.948
You're not gonna mention
the coincidence


143
00:14:57.023 --> 00:14:59.697
that you also live in Washington, D.C.?

144
00:14:59.775 --> 00:15:01.277
How did you know that?

145
00:15:01.360 --> 00:15:02.987
Have we met before?

146
00:15:03.070 --> 00:15:04.697
I've certainly seen you before,

147
00:15:04.780 --> 00:15:07.078
although you may not have seen me.

148
00:15:07.158 --> 00:15:09.411
So, Miss Scarlet, does this mean that
you live in Washington, too?


149
00:15:09.493 --> 00:15:10.460
Sure do.

150
00:15:10.536 --> 00:15:13.460
Does anyone here
not live in Washington D.C.?


151
00:15:13.539 --> 00:15:14.711
I don't.

152
00:15:14.790 --> 00:15:17.543
Yes, but you work for the United
Nations. That's a government job.


153
00:15:18.628 --> 00:15:20.301
And the rest of us all live in
a government town.


154
00:15:20.379 --> 00:15:22.928
Anyone here not earn their living from
the government, one way or another?


155
00:15:23.549 --> 00:15:26.553
Wadsworth, where's our host,
and why have we been brought here?


156
00:15:33.768 --> 00:15:36.442
Good evening.
You're eagerly awaited.


157
00:15:37.897 --> 00:15:40.116
Are you locking me in?
I'll take the key.


158
00:15:40.191 --> 00:15:41.613
Over my dead body, sir.

159
00:15:41.692 --> 00:15:42.864
May I take your bag?

160
00:15:42.943 --> 00:15:44.490
No. I'll leave it
here 'till I need it.

161
00:15:44.570 --> 00:15:46.538
It contains evidence,
I presume?


162
00:15:46.614 --> 00:15:49.413
It contains surprises, my friend.
That's what it contains, surprises.


163
00:15:51.327 --> 00:15:54.251
Ladies and gentlemen,
may I present Mr. Boddy.


164
00:15:55.623 --> 00:15:57.125
What are they all doing here?

165
00:15:57.208 --> 00:15:58.710
Eating dinner.

166
00:15:58.793 --> 00:16:00.841
Do sit down, Mr. Boddy.

167
00:16:00.920 --> 00:16:02.092
Thanks.

168
00:16:05.341 --> 00:16:06.763
No, you can take that away, honey.

169
00:16:13.641 --> 00:16:15.564
Look! I demand to know
what's going on.


170
00:16:15.643 --> 00:16:18.647
Now, why have we all been dragged
out here to this horrible place?


171
00:16:18.729 --> 00:16:21.903
Well, I believe we all received a letter.

172
00:16:21.982 --> 00:16:23.325
My letter says,

173
00:16:23.401 --> 00:16:26.655
"it will be to your advantage
to be present on this date.


174
00:16:26.737 --> 00:16:30.537
"Because Mr. Boddy will bring to an end
a certain long-standing, confidential,


175
00:16:30.616 --> 00:16:33.290
"and painful financial liability."

176
00:16:33.536 --> 00:16:34.833
It is signed, "A friend."

177
00:16:35.037 --> 00:16:36.380
I received a similar letter.

178
00:16:36.455 --> 00:16:37.581
So did we. Didn't we?

179
00:16:37.665 --> 00:16:40.088
I also received a letter.

180
00:16:40.167 --> 00:16:43.011
No, thanks, Yvette. I just ate.

181
00:16:43.129 --> 00:16:44.631
Now how did you know her name?

182
00:16:44.797 --> 00:16:46.515
We know each other.

183
00:16:46.590 --> 00:16:47.967
Don't we, dear?

184
00:16:49.135 --> 00:16:52.230
Forgive my curiosity, Mr. Boddy,
but did your letter say the same thing?


185
00:16:52.304 --> 00:16:54.557
- No.
- I see.


186
00:16:56.976 --> 00:16:59.980
Can I interest any of you
in fruit or dessert?


187
00:17:02.982 --> 00:17:05.076
In that case, may I suggest
we adjourn to the study


188
00:17:05.151 --> 00:17:07.199
for coffee and brandy,

189
00:17:07.278 --> 00:17:10.657
at which point I believe our unknown
host will reveal his intentions.


190
00:17:14.326 --> 00:17:15.873
There's no one here.

191
00:17:15.953 --> 00:17:19.878
Please help yourself to brandy
and be seated.


192
00:17:29.425 --> 00:17:31.348
Mind if I smoke?

193
00:17:50.488 --> 00:17:51.956
Ladies and gentlemen,

194
00:17:52.031 --> 00:17:55.956
I'm instructed to explain to you what
you all have in common with each other.


195
00:17:56.035 --> 00:17:58.709
Unless you would care to do the honors,
Mr. Boddy?


196
00:17:58.788 --> 00:18:01.166
Why me? Do they know who I am?

197
00:18:01.290 --> 00:18:03.793
I don't think so. You've never identified
yourself to them, I believe.


198
00:18:03.876 --> 00:18:06.425
It's a hoax. I suggest we all leave.

199
00:18:06.504 --> 00:18:08.802
I'm sorry, sir.
You cannot leave this house!


200
00:18:08.881 --> 00:18:10.258
No? Who's gonna stop me?

201
00:18:10.382 --> 00:18:13.101
There's no way out.
All the windows have bars.


202
00:18:13.177 --> 00:18:14.520
All the doors are locked.

203
00:18:14.595 --> 00:18:15.972
This is an outrage.
You can't hold us prisoner!


204
00:18:17.223 --> 00:18:18.315
He's right!

205
00:18:18.390 --> 00:18:20.734
Ladies and gentlemen, please.
Please return to the study.


206
00:18:20.810 --> 00:18:22.357
Everything will be explained.

207
00:18:23.729 --> 00:18:25.652
You, too, Mr. Boddy.

208
00:18:25.731 --> 00:18:27.199
Other way!

209
00:18:35.282 --> 00:18:37.125
You can't get out that way.

210
00:18:37.201 --> 00:18:38.418
Why not? It's only glass.

211
00:19:02.268 --> 00:19:05.067
Ladies and gentlemen,
you all have one thing in common.


212
00:19:05.145 --> 00:19:06.738
You're all being blackmailed.

213
00:19:06.814 --> 00:19:08.782
For some considerable time,

214
00:19:08.858 --> 00:19:10.485
all of you have been paying
what you can afford,


215
00:19:10.568 --> 00:19:12.241
and in some cases
more than you can afford,


216
00:19:12.319 --> 00:19:14.617
to someone who
threatens to expose you,


217
00:19:14.697 --> 00:19:17.450
and none of you know who's
blackmailing you. Do you?


218
00:19:17.825 --> 00:19:19.702
Please! I've never heard anything
so ridiculous!


219
00:19:19.785 --> 00:19:21.253
Nobody could blackmail me.

220
00:19:21.328 --> 00:19:24.127
My life is an open book.
I've never done anything wrong.


221
00:19:26.166 --> 00:19:29.136
Anybody else wish to deny it?

222
00:19:33.507 --> 00:19:34.929
Very well.

223
00:19:35.009 --> 00:19:36.932
As everyone here is in the same boat,

224
00:19:37.011 --> 00:19:38.729
there's no harm in my revealing
some details.


225
00:19:38.804 --> 00:19:40.556
And my instructions are to do so.

226
00:19:40.639 --> 00:19:41.856
Thank you, Yvette.

227
00:19:49.148 --> 00:19:52.118
Don't you think you might
spare us this humiliation.


228
00:19:52.192 --> 00:19:54.160
I'm sorry.

229
00:19:55.487 --> 00:19:58.616
Professor Plum, you were once
a professor of psychiatry,


230
00:19:58.699 --> 00:20:01.623
specializing in helping paranoid
and homicidal lunatics


231
00:20:01.702 --> 00:20:03.079
suffering from delusions of grandeur.

232
00:20:03.162 --> 00:20:04.630
Yes, but now I work for
the United Nations.


233
00:20:04.705 --> 00:20:07.629
No, your work has not changed. But
you don't practice medicine at the UN.


234
00:20:07.708 --> 00:20:10.882
His license to practice has been lifted.
Correct?


235
00:20:10.961 --> 00:20:12.588
Why? What did he do?

236
00:20:12.671 --> 00:20:14.799
You know what doctors aren't allowed to
do with their lady patients?


237
00:20:14.882 --> 00:20:16.429
- Yeah.
- Well, he did.


238
00:20:16.508 --> 00:20:18.510
How disgusting!

239
00:20:18.594 --> 00:20:22.019
Are you making moral judgments,
Mrs. Peacock?


240
00:20:22.097 --> 00:20:25.351
How then do you justify taking bribes

241
00:20:25.434 --> 00:20:27.107
in return for delivering your husband.

242
00:20:27.186 --> 00:20:28.733
Senator Peacock's vote
to certain lobbyists?


243
00:20:28.812 --> 00:20:31.782
My husband's a paid consultant.
There's nothing wrong with that.


244
00:20:31.857 --> 00:20:34.781
Not if it's publicly declared, perhaps.

245
00:20:34.860 --> 00:20:35.907
But if the payment is delivered by

246
00:20:35.986 --> 00:20:37.954
slipping used greenbacks
in plain envelopes


247
00:20:38.030 --> 00:20:40.783
under the door of the men's room, how
would you describe that transaction?


248
00:20:40.866 --> 00:20:41.833
I'd say it stinks.

249
00:20:41.909 --> 00:20:43.286
How would you know?
When were you in that men's room?


250
00:20:43.369 --> 00:20:44.336
So it's true?

251
00:20:44.411 --> 00:20:46.834
No. It's a vicious lie!

252
00:20:46.914 --> 00:20:48.757
I'm sure we're all glad to hear that.

253
00:20:48.832 --> 00:20:50.334
But you've been paying
blackmail for over a year now


254
00:20:50.417 --> 00:20:53.341
to keep that story out of the papers.

255
00:20:53.420 --> 00:20:55.422
Well, I am willing to believe you.

256
00:20:55.547 --> 00:20:57.800
I, too, am being blackmailed
for something I didn't do.


257
00:20:57.883 --> 00:20:59.305
- Me, too.
- And me.


258
00:20:59.385 --> 00:21:01.058
- Not me.
- You're not being blackmailed?


259
00:21:01.553 --> 00:21:05.228
I'm being blackmailed all right.
But I did what I'm being blackmailed for.


260
00:21:05.307 --> 00:21:06.729
What did you do?

261
00:21:06.809 --> 00:21:08.231
To be perfectly frank,

262
00:21:08.310 --> 00:21:11.314
I run a specialized hotel and a
telephone service which provides


263
00:21:11.397 --> 00:21:14.401
gentlemen with the company
of a young lady for a short while.


264
00:21:14.525 --> 00:21:15.993
Yeah?

265
00:21:16.068 --> 00:21:18.912
What's the phone number?

266
00:21:19.113 --> 00:21:21.161
So how did you know
Colonel Mustard works in Washington?


267
00:21:21.240 --> 00:21:22.537
Is he one of your clients?

268
00:21:22.616 --> 00:21:24.289
- Certainly not.
- I was asking Miss Scarlet.


269
00:21:24.368 --> 00:21:25.745
Well, you tell them it's not true.

270
00:21:25.828 --> 00:21:26.920
It's not true.

271
00:21:26.996 --> 00:21:28.498
- Is that true?
- No, it's not true.


272
00:21:28.580 --> 00:21:30.799
- Aha! So it is true!
- A double negative.


273
00:21:30.874 --> 00:21:32.547
A double negative?
Do you mean you have photographs?


274
00:21:32.710 --> 00:21:35.133
That sounds like a confession to me.
In fact, the double negative


275
00:21:35.212 --> 00:21:37.306
has led to proof positive.
I'm afraid you gave yourself away.


276
00:21:37.381 --> 00:21:39.930
Are you trying to make me look stupid
in front of the other guests?


277
00:21:40.009 --> 00:21:41.261
You don't need any help from me, sir.

278
00:21:41.343 --> 00:21:43.016
That's right!

279
00:21:43.095 --> 00:21:46.019
Seriously, I don't see what's so terrible
about Colonel Mustard


280
00:21:46.098 --> 00:21:49.022
visiting a house of ill fame.
Most soldiers do, don't they?


281
00:21:49.101 --> 00:21:50.353
Please.

282
00:21:50.436 --> 00:21:53.360
But he holds a sensitive security post
in the Pentagon.


283
00:21:53.439 --> 00:21:55.407
And, Colonel,
you drive a very expensive car


284
00:21:55.482 --> 00:21:57.359
for someone who lives
on a colonel's pay.


285
00:21:57.443 --> 00:22:00.322
I don't. I came into money during the
war when I lost my mommy and daddy.


286
00:22:03.532 --> 00:22:06.376
Mrs. White, you've been paying our
friend the blackmailer


287
00:22:06.452 --> 00:22:09.706
ever since your husband died under,
shall we say, mysterious circumstances.


288
00:22:11.623 --> 00:22:12.966
Why is that funny?

289
00:22:13.042 --> 00:22:16.421
I see. That's why he was lying
on his back. In his coffin.


290
00:22:16.587 --> 00:22:18.180
I didn't kill him.

291
00:22:18.255 --> 00:22:19.882
Then why are you
paying the blackmailer?


292
00:22:19.965 --> 00:22:21.808
I don't want a scandal, do I?

293
00:22:21.884 --> 00:22:24.728
We had had a very
humiliating public confrontation.


294
00:22:24.845 --> 00:22:27.189
He was deranged. 
He was a lunatic.

295
00:22:27.306 --> 00:22:30.355
He didn't actually seem to
like me very much.


296
00:22:30.434 --> 00:22:31.981
He threatened to kill me in public.

297
00:22:32.061 --> 00:22:33.483
Why would he want
to kill you in public?

298
00:22:33.562 --> 00:22:36.031
I think she meant
he threatened in public to kill her.


299
00:22:36.106 --> 00:22:38.700
Was that his final word on the matter?

300
00:22:38.776 --> 00:22:41.154
Being killed is pretty final,
wouldn't you say?


301
00:22:41.236 --> 00:22:44.706
And yet, he was the one who died.
Not you, Mrs. White. Not you.


302
00:22:44.782 --> 00:22:46.375
What did he do for a living?

303
00:22:46.450 --> 00:22:50.296
He was a scientist. 
Nuclear physics.

304
00:22:50.370 --> 00:22:52.372
What was he like?

305
00:22:52.456 --> 00:22:55.084
He was always
a rather stupidly optimistic man.


306
00:22:55.167 --> 00:22:57.636
I mean, I'm afraid It came as a great
shock to him when he died.


307
00:22:57.711 --> 00:22:59.713
But he was found dead at home.
His head had been cut off.


308
00:22:59.797 --> 00:23:01.765
And so had his...

309
00:23:01.840 --> 00:23:03.217
You know.

310
00:23:05.052 --> 00:23:06.895
I had been out
all evening at the movies.

311
00:23:06.970 --> 00:23:08.017
Do you miss him?

312
00:23:08.180 --> 00:23:11.855
Well, it's a matter of life after death.
Now that he's dead, I have a life.


313
00:23:11.934 --> 00:23:13.311
But he was your second husband.

314
00:23:13.393 --> 00:23:15.316
Your first husband also disappeared.

315
00:23:15.395 --> 00:23:17.864
But that was his job.
He was an illusionist.


316
00:23:17.940 --> 00:23:19.112
But he never reappeared.

317
00:23:19.191 --> 00:23:21.364
He wasn't a very good illusionist.

318
00:23:22.194 --> 00:23:24.663
I have something to say.

319
00:23:26.156 --> 00:23:29.660
I'm not gonna wait for Wadsworth
here to unmask me.


320
00:23:29.743 --> 00:23:32.166
I work for the State Department,

321
00:23:32.246 --> 00:23:33.543
and I'm a homosexual.

322
00:23:36.875 --> 00:23:40.175
I feel no personal shame
or guilt about this,


323
00:23:40.254 --> 00:23:45.101
but I must keep it a secret
or I'll lose my job on security grounds.


324
00:23:47.261 --> 00:23:48.729
Thank you.

325
00:23:51.765 --> 00:23:53.233
Well,

326
00:23:54.893 --> 00:23:57.772
that just leaves Mr. Boddy.

327
00:23:57.855 --> 00:23:59.198
What's your little secret?

328
00:23:59.273 --> 00:24:01.150
His secret? Haven't you guessed?

329
00:24:01.233 --> 00:24:03.110
He's the one who's blackmailing you.

330
00:24:04.403 --> 00:24:05.871
You bastard!

331
00:24:05.946 --> 00:24:08.745
Put 'em up!

332
00:24:09.908 --> 00:24:10.909
Gentlemen,

333
00:24:12.452 --> 00:24:15.205
if you can't fight
fairly, don't fight at all.

334
00:24:15.289 --> 00:24:17.758
Nobody calls me a bastard!

335
00:24:19.168 --> 00:24:21.216
Was that necessary,
Mrs. White?


336
00:24:21.295 --> 00:24:22.467
WADSWORTH Wait, wait!

337
00:24:22.588 --> 00:24:24.511
The police are coming.

338
00:24:24.590 --> 00:24:26.558
- No, no!
- No!


339
00:24:26.633 --> 00:24:28.180
Listen!

340
00:24:28.260 --> 00:24:30.183
Blackmail depends on secrecy.

341
00:24:30.262 --> 00:24:32.185
You've all admitted how
he's been able to blackmail you.


342
00:24:32.264 --> 00:24:33.607
All you have to
do is tell the police,

343
00:24:33.682 --> 00:24:35.684
he'll be convicted
and your troubles will be over.


344
00:24:35.767 --> 00:24:37.440
It's not so easy.

345
00:24:39.396 --> 00:24:41.194
You'll never tell the police.

346
00:24:41.273 --> 00:24:43.526
Then I shall.
I have evidence in my possession.


347
00:24:43.609 --> 00:24:46.078
And this conversation
is being tape recorded.


348
00:24:46.153 --> 00:24:47.370
Point of order.

349
00:24:47.446 --> 00:24:50.199
Tape recordings aren't
admissible evidence.


350
00:24:50.282 --> 00:24:54.378
Ladies and gentlemen, the police
will be here in about 45 minutes.


351
00:24:54.453 --> 00:24:55.670
Tell them the truth,

352
00:24:55.787 --> 00:24:59.462
and Mr. Boddy will be behind bars.

353
00:24:59.541 --> 00:25:01.293
Where are you going this time?

354
00:25:01.376 --> 00:25:03.219
I think I can help them
make up their minds.


355
00:25:03.295 --> 00:25:04.968
Can I just get my little bag
from the hall?


356
00:25:14.806 --> 00:25:17.730
Who can guess
what's in here?


357
00:25:17.809 --> 00:25:20.232
The evidence against us, no doubt.

358
00:25:20.312 --> 00:25:21.905
We didn't know we were
meeting you tonight.


359
00:25:21.980 --> 00:25:22.981
Did you know you were meeting us?

360
00:25:23.065 --> 00:25:24.157
Yes.

361
00:25:24.274 --> 00:25:26.447
What were you told, precisely?

362
00:25:26.526 --> 00:25:27.994
Merely, that you were all meeting to

363
00:25:28.070 --> 00:25:29.697
discuss our little
financial arrangements.


364
00:25:29.780 --> 00:25:31.703
And if I didn't appear,

365
00:25:31.782 --> 00:25:34.376
Wadsworth would be informing
the police about it all.


366
00:25:35.077 --> 00:25:39.002
Naturally, I could hardly resist
putting in an appearance.


367
00:25:39.289 --> 00:25:41.587
Excuse me.

368
00:25:41.708 --> 00:25:43.756
Open them.

369
00:25:45.295 --> 00:25:46.717
Why not?

370
00:25:48.799 --> 00:25:52.724
I enjoy getting presents
from strange men.


371
00:26:01.353 --> 00:26:03.230
A candlestick?

372
00:26:03.313 --> 00:26:05.236
What's this for?

373
00:26:50.986 --> 00:26:54.741
In your hands,
you each have a lethal weapon.


374
00:26:58.076 --> 00:27:00.499
If you denounce me to the police,

375
00:27:00.579 --> 00:27:03.833
you will also be
exposed and humiliated.


376
00:27:04.416 --> 00:27:07.169
I'll see to that in court.

377
00:27:08.086 --> 00:27:11.511
But if one of you kills Wadsworth now,

378
00:27:11.590 --> 00:27:14.639
no one but the seven
of us will ever know.


379
00:27:17.179 --> 00:27:19.648
He has the key to the front door,

380
00:27:19.723 --> 00:27:24.274
which he said would only be opened
over his dead body.


381
00:27:28.940 --> 00:27:32.911
I suggest we take
him up on that offer.

382
00:27:37.741 --> 00:27:40.836
The only way to avoid finding yourselves
on the front pages,


383
00:27:40.911 --> 00:27:45.007
is for one of
you to kill Wadsworth now.

384
00:27:56.635 --> 00:27:58.683
- It's not Wadsworth!
- Is he alive?


385
00:27:58.762 --> 00:27:59.809
Mr. Boddy.

386
00:27:59.888 --> 00:28:01.390
Stand back! Give him air!

387
00:28:01.473 --> 00:28:02.850
Let me see.

388
00:28:09.272 --> 00:28:10.694
He's dead!

389
00:28:10.774 --> 00:28:13.698
- Who had the gun?
- I did.


390
00:28:13.777 --> 00:28:15.450
- Then you shot him!
- I didn't!


391
00:28:15.529 --> 00:28:17.952
Well, you had the gun.
If you didn't shoot him, who did?


392
00:28:19.783 --> 00:28:21.831
Nobody! Look.
There's no gunshot wound.


393
00:28:21.910 --> 00:28:25.210
Somebody tried to grab the gun from
me in the dark and the gun went off.


394
00:28:25.288 --> 00:28:27.586
Look! The bullet broke that vase
on the mantle.


395
00:28:27.999 --> 00:28:29.626
Sorry. Excuse me.

396
00:28:30.877 --> 00:28:34.598
He's absolutely right. Look, there's a
bullet hole here in the wall. See that?


397
00:28:34.673 --> 00:28:37.222
- How did he die?
- I don't know!


398
00:28:37.300 --> 00:28:39.098
I'm not a forensic expert!

399
00:28:39.177 --> 00:28:41.225
One of us must have killed him.

400
00:28:41.304 --> 00:28:42.726
I didn't do it.

401
00:28:42.806 --> 00:28:44.729
I need a drink.

402
00:28:48.520 --> 00:28:50.272
Maybe he was poisoned.

403
00:28:50.355 --> 00:28:51.447
Aah!

404
00:28:53.483 --> 00:28:54.575
Aah!

405
00:28:54.734 --> 00:28:56.657
Mrs. Peacock, it's all right.

406
00:28:56.736 --> 00:28:58.659
We don't know anything.

407
00:28:58.738 --> 00:29:00.911
Sit down. Sit down.

408
00:29:02.492 --> 00:29:05.541
I had to stop her from screaming.

409
00:29:07.038 --> 00:29:09.006
Was the brandy poisoned?

410
00:29:09.082 --> 00:29:10.550
I don't know.

411
00:29:13.253 --> 00:29:15.176
Looks like we'll never know.

412
00:29:15.255 --> 00:29:16.677
Unless...

413
00:29:16.756 --> 00:29:18.724
Unless she dies, too.

414
00:29:35.275 --> 00:29:36.697
It's locked.

415
00:29:36.776 --> 00:29:38.198
Open up...

416
00:29:38.278 --> 00:29:39.700
- It must be the murderer!
- Why would he scream?


417
00:29:39.779 --> 00:29:41.201
He must have a victim in there.

418
00:29:41.281 --> 00:29:43.124
- My God! Yvette!
- My God!


419
00:29:46.578 --> 00:29:48.046
You're alive.

420
00:29:48.121 --> 00:29:49.543
- No thanks to you.
- What do you mean?


421
00:29:49.623 --> 00:29:51.751
You locked me up with a murderer,
you idiot!


422
00:29:51.833 --> 00:29:53.676
So the murderer is in this room?

423
00:29:53.752 --> 00:29:55.095
But where?

424
00:29:55.170 --> 00:29:56.763
Where? Here.

425
00:29:56.838 --> 00:29:59.842
We're all looking at him or her!

426
00:29:59.925 --> 00:30:02.098
It's what Mrs. 
White said in the study,

427
00:30:02.177 --> 00:30:03.679
one of you is the killer!

428
00:30:03.762 --> 00:30:05.309
How did you know we said that?

429
00:30:05.388 --> 00:30:06.514
I was listening.

430
00:30:06.598 --> 00:30:09.693
Why were you screaming in here
all by yourself?


431
00:30:09.768 --> 00:30:11.691
Because I am frightened. Me, too.

432
00:30:11.770 --> 00:30:13.693
I also drink the cognac. Mon Dieu!

433
00:30:13.772 --> 00:30:16.150
I can't stay here by myself.

434
00:30:19.152 --> 00:30:20.699
Come back to the study with us.

435
00:30:20.779 --> 00:30:22.201
With the murderer?

436
00:30:22.280 --> 00:30:24.783
There's safety in numbers, my dear.

437
00:30:38.797 --> 00:30:41.721
There's no indication of how he died?

438
00:30:41.800 --> 00:30:43.222
- No.
- This is terrible.


439
00:30:43.301 --> 00:30:44.723
This is absolutely terrible.

440
00:30:44.803 --> 00:30:46.726
It's not what I'd intended.

441
00:30:46.805 --> 00:30:47.931
My God!

442
00:30:48.014 --> 00:30:49.391
Not what you intended?

443
00:30:49.474 --> 00:30:51.397
So, you're not the butler?

444
00:30:51.476 --> 00:30:52.944
I'm not the butler,

445
00:30:53.019 --> 00:30:55.272
but I am a butler.
In fact, I was his butler.


446
00:30:55.355 --> 00:30:59.110
If he told you to invite us all to
his house, why did he arrive late?


447
00:30:59.192 --> 00:31:02.412
I invited you. In fact, 
I wrote the letters.

448
00:31:02.487 --> 00:31:03.659
It was all my idea.

449
00:31:03.738 --> 00:31:06.742
Wait a minute. 
I don't understand.

450
00:31:06.825 --> 00:31:09.749
Why did you invite us here
to meet your late employer?


451
00:31:09.828 --> 00:31:11.296
Were you assisting him
to blackmail us?


452
00:31:11.371 --> 00:31:12.748
Certainly not!

453
00:31:12.831 --> 00:31:14.925
I think you'd better explain.

454
00:31:15.000 --> 00:31:17.219
Please sit down, everyone.

455
00:31:37.689 --> 00:31:39.987
When I said I was Mr. 
Boddy's butler,

456
00:31:40.066 --> 00:31:41.739
this was both true and misleading.

457
00:31:41.818 --> 00:31:43.741
I was once his butler,

458
00:31:43.820 --> 00:31:45.367
but it was not his untimely death
this evening


459
00:31:45.447 --> 00:31:47.074
that brought my employment
with him to an end.


460
00:31:47.157 --> 00:31:48.625
When did it come to an end?

461
00:31:48.700 --> 00:31:52.250
When my wife decided to end her life.

462
00:31:52.329 --> 00:31:55.003
She, too, was being blackmailed by
this odious man


463
00:31:55.081 --> 00:31:56.253
who now lies dead before us.

464
00:31:56.333 --> 00:31:58.256
He hated my wife

465
00:31:58.335 --> 00:32:01.305
for the same reason
he hated all of you.

466
00:32:01.379 --> 00:32:04.223
He believed that you were all
thoroughly un-American.


467
00:32:07.719 --> 00:32:09.187
I'm sorry.

468
00:32:09.262 --> 00:32:11.890
For some reason he felt that it
was inappropriate


469
00:32:11.973 --> 00:32:14.192
for a senator to have a corrupt wife,

470
00:32:14.267 --> 00:32:16.895
for a doctor to take advantage
of his patients,


471
00:32:16.978 --> 00:32:20.073
for a wife to emasculate her husband,

472
00:32:20.231 --> 00:32:21.778
and so forth.

473
00:32:22.233 --> 00:32:23.234
But this is ridiculous.

474
00:32:23.318 --> 00:32:24.740
If he was such a patriotic American,

475
00:32:24.819 --> 00:32:25.991
why didn't he just report us
to the authorities?


476
00:32:26.071 --> 00:32:28.449
He decided to put his information
to good use


477
00:32:28.531 --> 00:32:29.657
and make a little money out of it.

478
00:32:29.741 --> 00:32:32.290
What could be
more American than that?


479
00:32:32.369 --> 00:32:33.791
What was your role in all this?

480
00:32:33.870 --> 00:32:36.168
I was a victim, too.

481
00:32:36.247 --> 00:32:38.716
At least, my wife was.

482
00:32:39.084 --> 00:32:41.337
She had friends who were

483
00:32:43.421 --> 00:32:44.422
socialists.

484
00:32:44.506 --> 00:32:46.725
My God.

485
00:32:50.762 --> 00:32:54.187
Well, we all make mistakes.

486
00:33:05.235 --> 00:33:06.987
Mr. Boddy threatened to give
my wife's name


487
00:33:07.070 --> 00:33:09.414
to the House Un-American Activities
Committee unless she named them.


488
00:33:09.489 --> 00:33:11.708
She refused, so he blackmailed her.

489
00:33:11.783 --> 00:33:14.707
We had no money.
And the price of his silence


490
00:33:14.786 --> 00:33:16.709
was that we work for him for nothing.
We were slaves.


491
00:33:16.788 --> 00:33:19.541
To make a long story short...

492
00:33:19.624 --> 00:33:20.716
Too late.

493
00:33:20.917 --> 00:33:23.215
The suicide of my wife
preyed on my mind


494
00:33:23.294 --> 00:33:26.013
and created a sense of injustice in me.

495
00:33:26.089 --> 00:33:28.717
I resolved to put Mr. 
Boddy behind bars.

496
00:33:28.800 --> 00:33:30.427
It seemed to me the
best way to do it

497
00:33:30.510 --> 00:33:33.138
and to free all of you from the same
burden of blackmail


498
00:33:33.221 --> 00:33:35.815
was to get everyone face to face,

499
00:33:35.890 --> 00:33:38.393
confront Mr. Boddy with his crimes,

500
00:33:38.476 --> 00:33:40.979
and then turn him over to the police.

501
00:33:41.104 --> 00:33:42.401
So, everything's explained.

502
00:33:44.107 --> 00:33:46.360
Nothing's explained.
We still don't know who killed him.


503
00:33:46.443 --> 00:33:49.868
The point is we've got to find out in the
next 39 minutes before the police arrive.


504
00:33:49.946 --> 00:33:52.574
My God. We can't have them
come here now.


505
00:33:52.657 --> 00:33:55.581
But how can we possibly find out
which of you did it?


506
00:33:55.660 --> 00:33:56.957
What do you mean,
"which of you did it"?


507
00:33:57.036 --> 00:33:58.253
Well, I didn't do it!

508
00:33:58.329 --> 00:34:01.458
Well, one of us did. We all had the
opportunity. We all had a motive.


509
00:34:01.541 --> 00:34:03.088
Great! We'll all go to the chair.

510
00:34:03.168 --> 00:34:05.136
- Maybe it wasn't one of us!
- Who else could it have been?


511
00:34:05.211 --> 00:34:06.258
Who else is in the house?

512
00:34:06.337 --> 00:34:07.429
- Only the cook!
- Only the cook!


513
00:34:07.505 --> 00:34:08.506
- The cook!
- The cook!


514
00:34:38.286 --> 00:34:41.631
Well, she's not here.

515
00:34:41.706 --> 00:34:42.878
Aah!

516
00:34:45.335 --> 00:34:47.258
I didn't do it!

517
00:34:47.337 --> 00:34:51.342
Somebody help me, please.

518
00:34:57.847 --> 00:34:59.269
- Don't touch it.

519
00:34:59.349 --> 00:35:00.771
That's evidence.

520
00:35:00.850 --> 00:35:02.318
Not for us.
We have to find out who did this.


521
00:35:02.393 --> 00:35:04.441
We can't take fingerprints.

522
00:35:04.521 --> 00:35:06.694
I think you'd better
explain yourself, Wadsworth.


523
00:35:06.773 --> 00:35:08.070
Me? Why me?

524
00:35:08.149 --> 00:35:09.696
Who would want to kill the cook?

525
00:35:09.776 --> 00:35:10.777
Dinner wasn't that bad.

526
00:35:10.860 --> 00:35:13.204
How can you make jokes
at a time like this?


527
00:35:13.279 --> 00:35:14.872
It's my defense mechanism.

528
00:35:14.948 --> 00:35:18.498
Some defense.
If I was the killer, I'd kill you next.


529
00:35:18.576 --> 00:35:22.080
I said "if." If.

530
00:35:23.998 --> 00:35:26.547
Hey, come on. There's only one
admitted killer here.


531
00:35:26.626 --> 00:35:27.923
And it is certainly
not me. It is her.

532
00:35:28.002 --> 00:35:29.470
I've admitted nothing.

533
00:35:29.546 --> 00:35:31.514
Well, you paid the blackmail.
How many husbands have you had?


534
00:35:31.589 --> 00:35:33.011
Mine or other women's?

535
00:35:33.091 --> 00:35:34.092
- Yours.
- Five.


536
00:35:34.175 --> 00:35:35.347
- Five?
- Yes. Just the five.


537
00:35:35.426 --> 00:35:37.349
Husbands should be like Kleenex,

538
00:35:37.428 --> 00:35:38.771
soft, strong, and disposable.

539
00:35:38.847 --> 00:35:41.771
You lure men to their deaths like
a spider with flies.


540
00:35:41.850 --> 00:35:43.523
Flies are where men
are most vulnerable.


541
00:35:43.601 --> 00:35:44.602
Right.

542
00:35:44.769 --> 00:35:47.693
Well, if it wasn't
you, then who was it?

543
00:35:47.772 --> 00:35:49.194
Who had the dagger, anyway?

544
00:35:49.274 --> 00:35:50.696
It was you, Mrs. 
Peacock, wasn't it?

545
00:35:50.775 --> 00:35:52.402
Yes. But I put it down.

546
00:35:52.485 --> 00:35:53.532
- Where?
- In the study.


547
00:35:53.611 --> 00:35:54.737
- When?
- I don't know.


548
00:35:54.821 --> 00:35:57.370
Before I fainted, or after I fainted...

549
00:35:57.448 --> 00:36:00.873
I don't know! But any of you
could have picked it up.


550
00:36:01.995 --> 00:36:05.670
Look. I suggest we take the cook's body
into the study.


551
00:36:05.748 --> 00:36:06.795
Why?

552
00:36:06.875 --> 00:36:10.049
I'm the butler.
I like to keep the kitchen tidy.


553
00:36:16.301 --> 00:36:17.723
- Look!
- What?


554
00:36:17.802 --> 00:36:19.896
The body's gone!

555
00:36:19.971 --> 00:36:21.063
What are you all staring at?

556
00:36:21.139 --> 00:36:22.106
Nothing.

557
00:36:22.181 --> 00:36:23.649
- Well, who's there?
- Nobody.


558
00:36:23.725 --> 00:36:25.193
- What do you mean?
- Nobody.


559
00:36:25.268 --> 00:36:27.817
No body, that's what we mean.
Mr. Boddy's body's gone.


560
00:36:28.271 --> 00:36:29.523
- Maybe he wasn't dead.
- He was!


561
00:36:29.731 --> 00:36:30.983
We should've made sure.

562
00:36:31.065 --> 00:36:32.408
How? By cutting his head off,
I suppose?


563
00:36:32.483 --> 00:36:34.110
- That was uncalled for.
- Where is he?


564
00:36:34.193 --> 00:36:36.616
We'd better look for him.

565
00:36:48.249 --> 00:36:52.174
Well, he couldn't have been dead.

566
00:36:52.253 --> 00:36:55.257
He was. At least, 
I thought he was.

567
00:36:55.340 --> 00:36:57.843
What difference does it make now?

568
00:36:57.926 --> 00:36:59.894
Makes quite a difference to him.

569
00:36:59.969 --> 00:37:02.848
Maybe there is life after death.

570
00:37:02.931 --> 00:37:04.854
Life after death's as improbable

571
00:37:04.933 --> 00:37:07.027
as sex after marriage.

572
00:37:07.143 --> 00:37:10.192
Maybe Mr. Boddy killed the cook!

573
00:37:10.271 --> 00:37:11.318
'Yes!
'Yes!


574
00:37:11.397 --> 00:37:13.024
How?

575
00:37:17.153 --> 00:37:18.530
I don't know.

576
00:37:18.696 --> 00:37:21.950
Well, if you'll excuse me. I have to...

577
00:37:22.659 --> 00:37:25.412
- ls there a little girl's room in the hall?
- Oui.oui. Madame.


578
00:37:25.703 --> 00:37:29.173
No, I just want to powder my nose.

579
00:37:31.042 --> 00:37:32.339
What's this, Wadsworth?

580
00:37:32.418 --> 00:37:35.843
I'm afraid those are the negatives to
which Colonel Mustard earlier referred.


581
00:37:35.922 --> 00:37:36.923
My God.

582
00:37:37.048 --> 00:37:38.345
Were you planning to blackmail him,
Wadsworth?


583
00:37:38.424 --> 00:37:41.223
Certainly not.
I'd obtained them for the colonel


584
00:37:41.302 --> 00:37:42.349
and I was going to give them back

585
00:37:42.428 --> 00:37:44.351
as soon as Mr. 
Boddy was unmasked.

586
00:37:44.430 --> 00:37:48.151
Very pretty. Would you like to see
these, Yvette? They might shock you.


587
00:37:48.226 --> 00:37:49.819
No, merci. I am a lady.

588
00:37:49.894 --> 00:37:52.147
How do you know what kind of
pictures they are if you're such a lady?


589
00:37:52.230 --> 00:37:53.322
What sort of pictures are they?

590
00:37:53.398 --> 00:37:55.025
They're my pictures and
I'd like them back please.


591
00:37:55.108 --> 00:37:57.531
No. I'm afraid there's something in
them that concerns me, too.


592
00:37:57.610 --> 00:37:59.032
Let me see.

593
00:37:59.112 --> 00:38:02.036
My.
Nobody can get into that position.


594
00:38:02.115 --> 00:38:03.537
Sure they can.

595
00:38:03.616 --> 00:38:05.539
Let me show you.

596
00:38:05.618 --> 00:38:07.086
Get off me.

597
00:38:07.203 --> 00:38:08.204
Aah!

598
00:38:15.753 --> 00:38:17.005
It's Mr. Boddy!

599
00:38:17.088 --> 00:38:19.011
He's attacking her.

600
00:38:19.090 --> 00:38:20.091
Aah!

601
00:38:23.469 --> 00:38:25.392
No. No, he's dead.

602
00:38:25.471 --> 00:38:27.769
Mr. Boddy. Dead again!

603
00:38:27.849 --> 00:38:29.066
My God.

604
00:38:29.142 --> 00:38:30.564
She's going to faint.

605
00:38:30.643 --> 00:38:32.065
Somebody catch her!

606
00:38:32.145 --> 00:38:33.818
I'll catch her.
Fall into my arms.


607
00:38:35.732 --> 00:38:36.824
Sorry.

608
00:38:36.899 --> 00:38:38.276
You've got blood on your hands.

609
00:38:39.736 --> 00:38:41.613
I didn't do it!

610
00:38:42.739 --> 00:38:46.243
He's got new injuries.
Well, he's certainly dead now.


611
00:38:46.325 --> 00:38:48.453
Why would anyone
want to kill him twice?


612
00:38:48.536 --> 00:38:49.879
Seems so unnecessary.

613
00:38:49.954 --> 00:38:51.126
That's what we call overkill.

614
00:38:51.205 --> 00:38:52.331
What we call psychotic.

615
00:38:52.415 --> 00:38:54.133
Unless he wasn't dead before.

616
00:38:54.208 --> 00:38:55.630
What's the difference?

617
00:38:55.710 --> 00:38:58.133
That's what we're trying to find out!
We're trying to find out


618
00:38:58.212 --> 00:39:00.635
who killed him, and where,
and with what!


619
00:39:00.715 --> 00:39:01.967
There's no need to shout!

620
00:39:02.050 --> 00:39:04.303
I'm not shouting!

621
00:39:04.927 --> 00:39:06.554
All right, lam!

622
00:39:06.637 --> 00:39:09.516
I'm shouting! I'm shouting! I'm...

623
00:39:20.443 --> 00:39:23.617
Okay, put the corpses on the sofa.

624
00:39:24.655 --> 00:39:26.077
Ladies first.

625
00:39:38.503 --> 00:39:40.471
Careful. Don't get blood on the sofa.

626
00:39:40.546 --> 00:39:43.675
How do we do this?
The dagger will go further into her back.


627
00:39:43.883 --> 00:39:45.476
Tip her forward over the arm.

628
00:39:50.807 --> 00:39:52.309
Now Mr. Boddy.

629
00:39:54.352 --> 00:39:55.524
Ready.

630
00:39:58.356 --> 00:39:59.778
A little higher.

631
00:39:59.857 --> 00:40:01.279
There we go.

632
00:40:05.363 --> 00:40:07.741
Now. Who...

633
00:40:08.866 --> 00:40:11.415
Who had access to the candlestick?

634
00:40:11.494 --> 00:40:13.462
- All of us.
- It was given to you.


635
00:40:13.538 --> 00:40:14.960
Yeah, but I dropped it on the table.

636
00:40:15.039 --> 00:40:17.212
Anyone could've picked it up. You, him.

637
00:40:17.291 --> 00:40:19.134
Look. We still have these weapons,

638
00:40:19.210 --> 00:40:22.305
the gun, the rope, the wrench,
the lead pipe.


639
00:40:22.380 --> 00:40:25.805
Let's put them all in this cupboard
and lock it.


640
00:40:25.883 --> 00:40:28.056
There's a homicidal maniac about.

641
00:40:28.136 --> 00:40:29.683
- Good idea.
- Good idea.


642
00:40:30.388 --> 00:40:32.231
- What are you doing with the key?
- Putting it in my pocket.


643
00:40:32.306 --> 00:40:33.899
- Why?
- To keep it safe, obviously.


644
00:40:33.975 --> 00:40:36.444
That means that you can
open it whenever you want.


645
00:40:36.519 --> 00:40:38.863
- But it also means that you can't.
- What if you're the murderer?


646
00:40:38.938 --> 00:40:39.985
I'm not.

647
00:40:40.064 --> 00:40:41.281
But what if you are?

648
00:40:41.357 --> 00:40:43.780
Well, it's got to be put somewhere.
If I've got it, I know I'm safe.


649
00:40:43.860 --> 00:40:45.954
We don't know that we are.

650
00:40:46.028 --> 00:40:47.951
I've an idea. We'll throw it away.

651
00:40:48.030 --> 00:40:49.077
Good idea!

652
00:40:49.157 --> 00:40:50.409
- Wonderful!
- Right away! Brilliant.


653
00:40:55.913 --> 00:40:57.085
Sorry.

654
00:40:58.916 --> 00:41:00.543
Sorry.

655
00:41:00.626 --> 00:41:02.094
Can we help?

656
00:41:02.170 --> 00:41:05.049
I'm sorry. I didn't mean to disturb
the whole household,


657
00:41:05.131 --> 00:41:08.010
but my car broke down out here

658
00:41:08.092 --> 00:41:11.016
and I was wondering
if I could use your phone.


659
00:41:11.095 --> 00:41:12.472
Just a moment please.

660
00:41:26.694 --> 00:41:28.196
Very well, sir.

661
00:41:28.279 --> 00:41:30.373
Would you care to come in?

662
00:41:30.907 --> 00:41:32.329
Well, where is it?

663
00:41:32.408 --> 00:41:33.830
What, the body?

664
00:41:33.910 --> 00:41:35.332
The phone. What body?

665
00:41:35.411 --> 00:41:37.834
There's no body. Nobody.
There's nobody in the study.


666
00:41:37.914 --> 00:41:39.336
- No!
- No!


667
00:41:39.540 --> 00:41:40.837
But I think there's
a phone in the lounge.

668
00:41:40.917 --> 00:41:42.294
Thank you.

669
00:41:48.925 --> 00:41:52.896
When you've finished your call, perhaps
you'd be good enough to wait here.


670
00:41:52.970 --> 00:41:54.472
Certainly.

671
00:42:06.817 --> 00:42:07.864
Aah!

672
00:42:08.569 --> 00:42:09.570
Where's the key?

673
00:42:09.654 --> 00:42:10.871
In my pocket.

674
00:42:10.947 --> 00:42:12.199
Not that key. The key to the cupboard.

675
00:42:12.281 --> 00:42:14.329
- With the weapons.
- Do you still wish me to throw it away?


676
00:42:14.408 --> 00:42:15.409
'Yes!
'Yes!


677
00:42:28.464 --> 00:42:31.388
Well, what now?

678
00:42:31.467 --> 00:42:32.889
Wadsworth, let me out.

679
00:42:32.969 --> 00:42:34.391
- No.
- Why not?


680
00:42:34.470 --> 00:42:36.268
We've got to know who did it.
We're all in this together now.


681
00:42:36.347 --> 00:42:38.691
If you leave,
I'll say that you killed them both.


682
00:42:38.766 --> 00:42:40.894
- Me, too.
- Me, too.


683
00:42:40.977 --> 00:42:42.900
Wadsworth, I'll make you sorry
you ever started this.


684
00:42:42.979 --> 00:42:44.902
One day, when we're alone together...

685
00:42:44.981 --> 00:42:48.485
Mrs. White, no man in his right mind
would be alone together with you.


686
00:42:48.567 --> 00:42:50.490
Well, I could use a drink.

687
00:42:50.569 --> 00:42:51.991
So could I.

688
00:42:52.071 --> 00:42:53.493
Just checking.

689
00:42:53.572 --> 00:42:54.789
Everything all right?

690
00:42:54.865 --> 00:42:57.209
Yep. Two corpses. 
Everything's fine.

691
00:43:00.288 --> 00:43:01.540
Anybody else want a whiskey?

692
00:43:01.622 --> 00:43:02.669
Yeah.

693
00:43:04.208 --> 00:43:05.630
All right, look.

694
00:43:05.710 --> 00:43:07.553
Pay attention, everybody.

695
00:43:09.005 --> 00:43:12.430
Wadsworth, am I right in thinking
there's nobody else in this house?


696
00:43:12.508 --> 00:43:13.600
No.

697
00:43:13.676 --> 00:43:15.303
Then there is someone else
in this house?


698
00:43:15.386 --> 00:43:17.935
- No, sorry. I said "no" meaning yes.
- "No" meaning yes?


699
00:43:18.014 --> 00:43:19.937
Look. I want a straight answer.

700
00:43:20.016 --> 00:43:23.771
Is there someone else or isn't there,
yes or no?


701
00:43:23.853 --> 00:43:24.945
No.

702
00:43:25.021 --> 00:43:26.819
No, there is,
or no there isn't?


703
00:43:26.897 --> 00:43:27.989
WADSWORTH Yes.

704
00:43:28.065 --> 00:43:29.738
Please!

705
00:43:30.818 --> 00:43:32.866
Don't you think we should get that man
out of the house


706
00:43:32.945 --> 00:43:34.913
before he finds out
what's been going on here?


707
00:43:34.989 --> 00:43:35.990
Yeah.

708
00:43:36.073 --> 00:43:37.916
How can we throw him outside
in this weather?


709
00:43:37.992 --> 00:43:40.336
If we let him stay in the house,
he may get suspicious.


710
00:43:40.411 --> 00:43:42.254
If we throw him out,
he may get even more suspicious.


711
00:43:42.330 --> 00:43:44.128
If I were him, 
I'd be suspicious already.

712
00:43:44.206 --> 00:43:47.050
Who cares? That guy doesn't matter.

713
00:43:47.126 --> 00:43:49.754
Let him stay locked up
for another half hour.


714
00:43:49.837 --> 00:43:52.090
The police will be here by then,

715
00:43:52.173 --> 00:43:55.427
and there are two dead bodies
in the study!


716
00:43:57.803 --> 00:43:59.430
Well, there's still some confusion

717
00:43:59.513 --> 00:44:01.140
as to whether or not there's
anybody else in this house.


718
00:44:01.223 --> 00:44:02.520
I told you there isn't.

719
00:44:02.600 --> 00:44:04.443
There isn't any confusion or
there isn't anybody else?


720
00:44:04.518 --> 00:44:06.941
- Either. Or both.
- Just give me a clear answer.


721
00:44:07.021 --> 00:44:10.446
- Certainly. What was the question?
- Ls there anybody else in the house?


722
00:44:10.524 --> 00:44:11.946
- No!
- No!


723
00:44:12.026 --> 00:44:15.872
That's what he says, but does he know?

724
00:44:15.946 --> 00:44:19.200
I suggest we handle this
in proper military fashion.


725
00:44:19.283 --> 00:44:21.456
We split up and search the house.

726
00:44:21.535 --> 00:44:22.582
Split Up?

727
00:44:22.661 --> 00:44:26.336
Yes. We have very little time left,
so we'll split up into pairs.


728
00:44:26.457 --> 00:44:27.424
- Pairs?
- Yes.


729
00:44:27.500 --> 00:44:29.844
Wait a minute. Suppose that
one of us is the murderer.


730
00:44:29.919 --> 00:44:31.011
If we split up into pairs,

731
00:44:31.087 --> 00:44:33.385
whichever one of us is left with
the killer might get killed.


732
00:44:33.464 --> 00:44:35.967
Then we would've discovered
who the murderer is.


733
00:44:36.050 --> 00:44:38.519
But the other half of the pair
would be dead!


734
00:44:38.594 --> 00:44:42.064
This is war, Peacock.
Casualties are inevitable.


735
00:44:42.139 --> 00:44:43.982
You cannot make an omelet
without breaking eggs.


736
00:44:44.058 --> 00:44:45.150
Every cook will tell you that.

737
00:44:45.226 --> 00:44:47.900
But look what happened to the cook.

738
00:44:48.854 --> 00:44:50.777
Colonel, are you willing to
take that chance?


739
00:44:50.856 --> 00:44:52.529
What choice have we?

740
00:44:52.608 --> 00:44:53.825
None.

741
00:44:53.901 --> 00:44:55.073
I suppose you're right.

742
00:44:55.152 --> 00:44:57.746
But it's dark upstairs.

743
00:44:57.822 --> 00:44:59.415
And I'm frightened of the dark.

744
00:44:59.490 --> 00:45:01.242
Will anyone go with me?

745
00:45:01.325 --> 00:45:02.702
- I will.
- I will.


746
00:45:02.785 --> 00:45:04.207
No, thank you.

747
00:45:04.286 --> 00:45:08.166
I suggest we all draw lots for partners.

748
00:45:28.978 --> 00:45:31.572
Ready? The two shortest together,

749
00:45:31.647 --> 00:45:34.571
the next two shortest together. Agreed?

750
00:45:34.650 --> 00:45:36.652
And I suggest that
the two shortest search the cellar,


751
00:45:36.735 --> 00:45:38.658
and so on, up.

